results.description:
Adaptive exponential integrate-and-fire (aeIF) neuron models for different cell types:

     - RS (Regular Spiking) pyramidal cells (excitatory)
     - RSw (weakly adapting Regular Spiking) pyramidal cell (excitatory)
     - FS (Fast Spiking) interneuron cells (inhibitory) with negligible adaptation.
     - LTS (Low Threshold Spiking) cortical cell (excitatory)
     - TC (ThalamoCortical) thalamic cell (excitatory)
     - RE (Reticular thalamic nucleus) thalamic cells (inhibitory)

This script reproduces Figure 1 of the following article:

Destexhe A (2009) Self-sustained asynchronous irregular states and Up-Down states inthalamic, cortical and thalamocortial networks of nonlinear integrate-and-fire neurons. J Computat Neurosci 27:493-506
DOI 10.1007/s10827-009-0164-4

In the figure we see the response of each cell type to a depolarizing current pulse of 0.25nA or a hyperpolarizing current pulse -0.25nA.
results.name: AdEx Neuron Models with PyNN

results.description:
A computational model for astrocyte-neuron interactions is developed to facilitate better understanding of the role of glial cells, specifically astrocytes, in synaptic and network level plasticity and learning. The developed model is complex, consisting of a large number of equations. In brief, the well-established biophysical and biochemical mechanisms are described for the neuronal compartments. The astrocyte compartment of the model contains several key mechanisms, including intracellular calcium and IP3, that are known to be involved in the regulation of cortical synapses. Background information for the construction of the model can be found in Manninen et al. (2017) and Manninen et al. (2018).  A classical stimulation protocol of long-term plasticity was used to test the model functionality. The integrated model was validated against typical neuronal spiking and astrocyte calcium excitability data. Further details of the model can be obtained in Havela et al. 2017. In summary, the model was able to capture the dynamical responses of both neurons and astrocytes during the simulation of the full model when varying the frequency of the stimuli and the volume of the postsynaptic neuron compartment.

Related code: https://senselab.med.yale.edu/modeldb/showmodel.cshtml?model=223648#tabs-1
results.name: Astrocyte-Neuron Interaction model

results.description: The dynamics of networks of sparsely connected excitatory and inhibitory integrate-and-fire neurons are studied analytically (and with simulations). The analysis reveals a rich repertoire of states, including synchronous states in which neurons fire regularly; asynchronous states with stationary global activity and very irregular individual cell activity; and states in which the global activity oscillates but individual cells fire irregularly, typically at rates lower than the global oscillation frequency. See paper for more and details. Brunel N (2000) Dynamics of sparsely connected networks of excitatory and inhibitory spiking neurons. J Comput Neurosci 8:183-208.
